  "text": "The Kafka ProduceRequest travels through the following chain from producer to broker:\n\n1. **KafkaProducer.send()** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/KafkaProducer.java:829) - The public API entry point where a user calls producer.send(record) with an optional callback.\n\n2. **RecordAccumulator.append()** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/internals/RecordAccumulator.java:275) - Called from KafkaProducer.doSend() at line 1029. This method accumulates the record into batches, handling partitioning, memory allocation, and buffering.\n\n3. **Sender.sendProducerData()** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/internals/Sender.java:357) - A private method called periodically by the Sender thread (invoked from run() at line 339). It checks which partitions have data ready to send, drains batches from the accumulator, and coordinates sending through sendProduceRequests().\n\n4. **NetworkClient.send()** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/NetworkClient.java:541) - Called from Sender.sendProduceRequest() at line 914. This method queues the ClientRequest for transmission over the network to the broker.\n\n5. **ReplicaManager.appendRecords()** (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaManager.scala:674) - The broker-side method that receives the produce request. It validates the request (checking required acks), appends records to the leader replica, and manages replication coordination.\n\nThe flow bridges the async, batched producer design (accumulating records efficiently) with the broker's log replication system. Records are batched in the accumulator for efficient transmission, the Sender thread converts batches to ProduceRequests, the NetworkClient transmits them, and the ReplicaManager on the broker handles persistence and replication."
}

